Hi, 

Glances is running quite well on the box I want to monitor, but nginx seems to have some kind of problem rewriting the URLs for Chrome to understand it correctly.

My setup is as follows : Nginx is locally listening on port 2443, and sslh is redirecting 443 requests to nginx when it's called from a web browser, and to port 22 when it's from an ssh connection.

Sometimes, when I tinker too much on my nginx conf file, URLs got rewritten with https://my.domain.com:2443/... which should not occur if the redirections are correctly done.

That's what's happening with Glances, the base URL is correct but every ressources (css for example) Chrome tries to retrieve, it tries on port 2443.

I'm pretty sure it's a nginx conf issue, but if someone can shed light on this for me that would help me understand quite some things related to regex in nginx conf files :)

Here's the bloc for glances (taken from the wiki)

```
location /glances/ {
        rewrite /glances/(.*) /$1 break;
        proxy_pass http://192.168.1.98:61208;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme; #doesn't do anything?
}
```

and on my / location 

```
location = / {
        if ($http_referer ~ "^https?://[^/]+/glances"){
                rewrite ^/(.*) https://$http_host/glances/$1 redirect;
        }
```

I guess some nginx expert will sort this in a blink of an eye but I'm lost 🗡

