Whenever a property in the header of a PLY asset is not recognized, the token parser does not advance the pointer properly to the number of occurrences, causing string-to-int to report zero, thus failing at gathering properties and at calculating proper byte offsets.

The problem is in PlyParser.cpp, lines 378 to 387:

    // parse the semantic of the element
    const char* szCur = pCur;
    pOut->eSemantic = PLY::Element::ParseSemantic(pCur,&pCur);
    if (PLY::EEST_INVALID == pOut->eSemantic)
    {
        // if the exact semantic can't be determined, just store
        // the original string identifier
        uintptr_t iDiff = (uintptr_t)pCur - (uintptr_t)szCur;
        pOut->szName = std::string(szCur,iDiff);
    }

pCur is not moved by PLY::Element::ParseSemantic, iDiff is thus zero (-> no string copied), and trying to get the number of element occurrences fails (line 392, pOut->NumOccur = strtoul10(pCur,&pCur);) because it is strtoul10 is fed with the element name. lot of other logical errors due to wrong parsing occurs in cascade.

